318
00:22:58,426 --> 00:23:03,805
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.
The doc had already gone home for the night.

319
00:23:03,806 --> 00:23:06,558
Poor bastard lay there till this morning.

320
00:23:06,642 --> 00:23:09,477
By then, hell, there weren't nothing we could do.

321
00:23:15,276 --> 00:23:16,860
What was his name?

322
00:23:20,114 --> 00:23:21,489
What did you say?

323
00:23:23,367 --> 00:23:25,744
I was just wondering if anyone knew his name.

324
00:23:25,828 --> 00:23:28,538
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

325
00:23:29,999 --> 00:23:33,376
It doesn't fuckin' matter what his name was.
He's dead.

326
00:23:52,730 --> 00:23:55,065
Hey...

327
00:23:55,149 --> 00:23:57,901
Anybody come at you yet?

328
00:23:59,403 --> 00:24:01,404
Anybody get to you yet?

329
00:24:02,531 --> 00:24:05,575
Hey, we all need friends in here.

330
00:24:05,660 --> 00:24:07,577
I could be a friend to you.

331
00:24:10,039 --> 00:24:11,706
Hey...

332
00:24:16,545 --> 00:24:18,421
Hard to get.

333
00:24:20,091 --> 00:24:21,758
I like that.

334
00:24:28,391 --> 00:24:31,685
RED: Andy kept pretty much to himself at first.

335
00:24:31,769 --> 00:24:34,229
I guess he had a lot on his mind,

336
00:24:34,313 --> 00:24:36,523
trying to adapt to life on the inside.

337
00:24:38,067 --> 00:24:40,777
It wasn't until a month went by
that he opened his mouth

338
00:24:40,861 --> 00:24:43,154
to say more than two words to somebody.

339
00:24:45,074 --> 00:24:47,117
As it turned out...

340
00:24:47,201 --> 00:24:49,119
that somebody was me.

341
00:24:52,707 --> 00:24:56,876
TANNOY: Officers Russell and Burwell
report to the duty officer.

342
00:24:57,920 --> 00:25:00,672
I'm Andy Dufresne.

343
00:25:00,756 --> 00:25:02,841
The wife-killing banker.

344
00:25:04,677 --> 00:25:06,386
Why did you do it?

345
00:25:06,470 --> 00:25:08,096
I didn't, since you ask.

346
00:25:08,180 --> 00:25:11,224
(Laughs) You're gonna fit right in!

347
00:25:11,309 --> 00:25:14,477
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

348
00:25:14,562 --> 00:25:17,897
- Heywood, what are you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

349
00:25:20,818 --> 00:25:23,611
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

350
00:25:23,696 --> 00:25:27,449
You think your shit smells sweeter than most.
Is that right?

351
00:25:27,533 --> 00:25:29,868
- What do you think?
- To tell you the truth,

352
00:25:29,952 --> 00:25:33,038
I haven't made up my mind. (Chuckles)

353
00:25:33,122 --> 00:25:37,208
I understand
you're a man that knows how to get things.

354
00:25:37,293 --> 00:25:40,795
I'm known to locate certain things,
from time to time.

355
00:25:40,880 --> 00:25:43,882
- I wonder if you might get me a rock hammer.
- A what?

356
00:25:43,966 --> 00:25:45,342
A rock hammer.

357
00:25:45,426 --> 00:25:47,719
- What is it, and why?
- What do you care?

358
00:25:49,597 --> 00:25:52,474
Well, if it was a toothbrush, I'd just quote a price,

359
00:25:52,558 --> 00:25:55,143
but then a toothbrush is a non-lethal object.

360
00:25:56,562 --> 00:25:58,271
Fair enough.

361
00:25:58,356 --> 00:26:00,815
A rock hammer
is about six or seven inches long.

362
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:02,525
Looks like a miniature pickaxe.

363
00:26:02,610 --> 00:26:03,735
Pickaxe?

364
00:26:03,819 --> 00:26:05,904
- For rocks.
- Rocks.

365
00:26:07,573 --> 00:26:09,741
Quartz?

366
00:26:09,825 --> 00:26:11,493
Quartz.

367
00:26:12,745 --> 00:26:15,121
And some mica.

368
00:26:15,206 --> 00:26:16,373
Shale.

369
00:26:17,458 --> 00:26:19,042
Limestone.

370
00:26:19,126 --> 00:26:21,044
So?

371
00:26:21,128 --> 00:26:23,213
So, I'm a rock hound.

372
00:26:23,297 --> 00:26:26,508
At least, I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again on a limited basis.

373
00:26:26,592 --> 00:26:28,718
Or maybe you want
to hammer somebody's skull.

374
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:30,261
No, sir.

375
00:26:31,389 --> 00:26:32,972
I have no enemies here.

376
00:26:33,057 --> 00:26:35,433
No? Wait a while.

377
00:26:36,977 --> 00:26:39,145
Word gets around.

378
00:26:39,230 --> 00:26:42,357
The Sisters have taken quite a liking to you.

379
00:26:42,441 --> 00:26:44,234
Especially Bogs.

380
00:26:45,319 --> 00:26:49,531
I don't suppose it would help any
if I explained to them I'm not homosexual.

381
00:26:49,615 --> 00:26:51,116
RED: Neither are they.

382
00:26:51,200 --> 00:26:53,910
You have to be human first. They don't qualify.

383
00:26:59,166 --> 00:27:03,711
Bull queers take by force.
It's all they want or understand.

384
00:27:03,796 --> 00:27:07,424
If I were you,
I'd grow eyes in the back of my head.

385
00:27:07,508 --> 00:27:08,842
Thanks for the advice.

386
00:27:08,926 --> 00:27:10,510
Well, that's free.

387
00:27:10,594 --> 00:27:12,846
You understand my concern.

388
00:27:12,930 --> 00:27:15,473
Well, if there's any trouble,
I won't use the hammer.

389
00:27:15,558 --> 00:27:19,769
Then I guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

390
00:27:21,230 --> 00:27:23,022
Did I miss something? What's funny?

391
00:27:23,107 --> 00:27:26,151
You'll understand
when you see the rock hammer.

392
00:27:28,028 --> 00:27:30,029
What's an item like this usually go for?

393
00:27:30,114 --> 00:27:33,158
Seven dollars in any rock and gem shop.

394
00:27:33,242 --> 00:27:35,952
My normal mark-up's 20 per cent.

395
00:27:35,953 --> 00:27:38,496
But this is a specialty item.

396
00:27:38,581 --> 00:27:41,166
The risk goes up, the price goes up.

397
00:27:41,167 --> 00:27:43,126
Let's make it an even ten bucks.

398
00:27:43,210 --> 00:27:45,086
Ten it is.

399
00:27:46,172 --> 00:27:48,590
Waste of money, if you ask me.

400
00:27:48,674 --> 00:27:50,216
Why's that?

401
00:27:51,302 --> 00:27:54,345
Folks around this joint love surprise inspections.

402
00:27:55,931 --> 00:27:58,224
If they find it, you're gonna lose it.

403
00:27:58,309 --> 00:28:00,435
If they do catch you with it, you don't know me.

404
00:28:00,519 --> 00:28:02,729
Mention my name, we never do business again.

405
00:28:02,813 --> 00:28:05,940
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now, you got that?

406
00:28:07,443 --> 00:28:08,860
I understand.

407
00:28:08,944 --> 00:28:10,361
Thank you...

408
00:28:10,362 --> 00:28:11,988
Mr. er...?

409
00:28:12,072 --> 00:28:14,532
Red. The name's Red.

410
00:28:14,533 --> 00:28:15,575
Red?

411
00:28:15,659 --> 00:28:18,411
Why do they call you that?

412
00:28:22,082 --> 00:28:24,167
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

413
00:28:32,134 --> 00:28:35,178
RED: I could see
why some of the boys took him for snobby.

414
00:28:35,262 --> 00:28:38,681
He had a quiet way about him.

415
00:28:38,766 --> 00:28:43,228
A walk and a talk
that just wasn't normal around here.

416
00:28:43,312 --> 00:28:44,854
He strolled...

417
00:28:44,939 --> 00:28:49,275
like a man in a park,
without a care or worry in the world.

418
00:28:49,360 --> 00:28:54,072
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

419
00:28:54,156 --> 00:28:58,326
Yeah. I think it would be fair to say...

420
00:28:58,327 --> 00:29:00,411
I liked Andy from the start.

421
00:29:02,164 --> 00:29:05,375
Let's go!
Some of us have got a schedule to keep.

422
00:29:08,671 --> 00:29:10,755
Move it! Come on. Move it!

423
00:29:14,385 --> 00:29:17,512
Bob, how are you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

424
00:29:27,231 --> 00:29:28,690
Easy.

425
00:29:28,774 --> 00:29:30,858
Keep it moving.

426
00:29:33,654 --> 00:29:34,904
Red...

427
00:29:55,426 --> 00:29:59,637
RED: Andy was right. I finally got the joke.

428
00:29:59,722 --> 00:30:04,225
It would take a man about 600 years
to tunnel under the wall with one of these.

429
00:30:08,564 --> 00:30:09,689
Book?

430
00:30:09,773 --> 00:30:11,649
Not today.

431
00:30:16,989 --> 00:30:19,073
- Book?
- No.

432
00:30:20,868 --> 00:30:22,076
Hey, Brooksy.

433
00:30:25,372 --> 00:30:27,457
Delivery for Dufresne.

434
00:30:34,548 --> 00:30:40,178
Book?

435
00:30:43,182 --> 00:30:45,308
Dufresne...

436
00:30:45,392 --> 00:30:47,560
Here's your book.

437
00:30:51,982 --> 00:30:53,650
Thanks.

438
00:30:57,488 --> 00:31:00,698
Dufresne! We're running low on Hexlite.

439
00:31:00,783 --> 00:31:02,867
Get on back and fetch us up some.

440
00:31:40,072 --> 00:31:42,031
If you get this in your eyes, it blinds you.

441
00:31:42,116 --> 00:31:44,867
Honey...hush.

442
00:31:51,959 --> 00:31:53,835
(Groans)

443
00:31:56,922 --> 00:31:59,340
That's it. You fight.

444
00:31:59,425 --> 00:32:01,008
It's better that way.

445
00:32:01,093 --> 00:32:02,885
(Screaming and yelling)

446
00:32:09,435 --> 00:32:12,270
RED: I wish I could tell you
that Andy fought the good fight,

447
00:32:12,354 --> 00:32:14,897
and the Sisters let him be.

448
00:32:14,982 --> 00:32:16,983
I wish I could tell you that.

449
00:32:17,067 --> 00:32:19,152
But prison is no fairy-tale world.

450
00:32:21,113 --> 00:32:23,239
He never said who did it.

451
00:32:23,323 --> 00:32:26,367
But we all knew.

452
00:32:26,452 --> 00:32:28,327
(Gate buzzer)

453
00:32:29,705 --> 00:32:32,582
Things went on like that for a while.

454
00:32:32,666 --> 00:32:35,293
Prison life consists of routine...

455
00:32:35,377 --> 00:32:37,587
and then more routine.

456
00:32:39,965 --> 00:32:43,801
Every so often,
Andy would show up with fresh bruises.

457
00:32:44,970 --> 00:32:47,013
The Sisters kept at him.

458
00:32:47,097 --> 00:32:51,225
Sometimes he was able to fight 'em off.
Sometimes not.

459
00:32:51,310 --> 00:32:54,562
And that's how it went for Andy.

460
00:32:54,646 --> 00:32:57,190
That was his routine.

461
00:32:57,274 --> 00:33:01,068
I do believe
those first two years were the worst for him.

462
00:33:01,153 --> 00:33:03,404
And I also believe,

463
00:33:03,489 --> 00:33:08,034
if things had gone on that way,
this place would have got the best of him.

464
00:33:08,118 --> 00:33:11,078
But then, in the spring of 1949,

465
00:33:11,163 --> 00:33:13,164
the powers that be decided that...

466
00:33:13,248 --> 00:33:16,667
The roof of the license-plate factory
needs resurfacing.

467
00:33:16,752 --> 00:33:19,504
I need a dozen volunteers for a week's work.

468
00:33:20,672 --> 00:33:22,799
As you know,

469
00:33:22,883 --> 00:33:26,594
special detail carries with it special privileges.

470
00:33:26,678 --> 00:33:28,763
RED: It was outdoor detail...

471
00:33:30,265 --> 00:33:33,851
..and May is one damn fine month
to be working outdoors.

472
00:33:33,936 --> 00:33:35,561
Stay in line there.

473
00:33:35,646 --> 00:33:38,564
More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.

474
00:33:40,067 --> 00:33:41,734
(Whispers)

475
00:33:42,945 --> 00:33:45,238
Wallace E Unger.

476
00:33:46,406 --> 00:33:48,866
Ellis Redding.

477
00:33:48,951 --> 00:33:51,786
Wouldn't you know it?

478
00:33:51,870 --> 00:33:54,455
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names.

479
00:33:54,540 --> 00:33:56,624
GUARD: Andrew Dufresne.

480
00:33:56,708 --> 00:34:00,253
RED: It only cost us a pack of smokes per man.

481
00:34:00,337 --> 00:34:03,047
I made my usual 20 per cent, of course.

482
00:34:03,131 --> 00:34:06,717
HADLEY: So, this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

483
00:34:06,802 --> 00:34:08,511
I say, "Yeah?"

484
00:34:08,595 --> 00:34:12,306
