Erle Stanley Gardners.

763
00:52:43,292 --> 00:52:46,836
Every evening,
I load up the cart and make my round.

764
00:52:46,837 --> 00:52:50,006
I enter the names on this clipboard here.

765
00:52:50,091 --> 00:52:53,551
Easy-peasy, Japanesey. Any questions?

766
00:52:53,636 --> 00:52:56,596
Brooks, how long have you been librarian?

767
00:52:56,681 --> 00:53:01,851
Oh...I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

768
00:53:01,936 --> 00:53:05,313
And in all that time,
have you ever had an assistant?

769
00:53:05,398 --> 00:53:07,983
No. No, not much to it, really.

770
00:53:08,067 --> 00:53:09,985
Well, why me? Why now?

771
00:53:10,069 --> 00:53:11,569
I don't know,

772
00:53:11,654 --> 00:53:14,990
but it'll be nice to have some company
down here for a change.

773
00:53:14,991 --> 00:53:17,075
HADLEY: Dufresne!

774
00:53:26,377 --> 00:53:28,461
That's him. That's the one.

775
00:53:36,012 --> 00:53:37,303
I'm Dekins.

776
00:53:37,388 --> 00:53:39,848
(Nervously) I was er...

777
00:53:39,932 --> 00:53:43,935
thinking about maybe setting up
some kind of trust fund for my kids' educations.

778
00:53:46,272 --> 00:53:47,731
Oh...

779
00:53:47,815 --> 00:53:49,482
I see.

780
00:53:50,943 --> 00:53:52,819
Well, erm...

781
00:53:54,196 --> 00:53:55,739
..why don't we have a seat,

782
00:53:55,823 --> 00:53:57,907
and talk it over?

783
00:54:00,453 --> 00:54:03,371
Brooks,
do you have a piece of paper and a pencil?

784
00:54:14,842 --> 00:54:16,551
Thanks.

785
00:54:16,635 --> 00:54:18,303
So...

786
00:54:19,555 --> 00:54:22,057
Mr. Dekins...

787
00:54:22,141 --> 00:54:26,603
And then Andy says to Mr. Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

788
00:54:26,687 --> 00:54:28,813
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

789
00:54:28,898 --> 00:54:31,566
As God is my witness, he did!

790
00:54:31,650 --> 00:54:35,028
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

791
00:54:35,112 --> 00:54:36,988
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

792
00:54:37,073 --> 00:54:38,448
My ass!

793
00:54:38,532 --> 00:54:39,741
Shook his hand.

794
00:54:39,825 --> 00:54:42,786
Hell, I...I near soiled myself! (Laughs)

795
00:54:42,870 --> 00:54:47,082
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

796
00:54:47,166 --> 00:54:48,500
and he would have been:

797
00:54:48,584 --> 00:54:50,126
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please"!

798
00:54:50,211 --> 00:54:51,961
Making a few friends, Andy?

799
00:54:53,005 --> 00:54:54,964
I wouldn't say "friends".

800
00:54:55,049 --> 00:54:59,052
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

801
00:54:59,136 --> 00:55:01,471
It's a wonderful pet to have.

802
00:55:01,555 --> 00:55:03,473
Got you out of the laundry, though.

803
00:55:03,557 --> 00:55:05,767
Well, it might do more than that.

804
00:55:05,851 --> 00:55:08,853
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

805
00:55:08,938 --> 00:55:11,648
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

806
00:55:11,732 --> 00:55:14,192
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

807
00:55:14,276 --> 00:55:19,531
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr. Dufresne, if you please?

808
00:55:19,615 --> 00:55:21,366
Ask the Warden for funds.

809
00:55:21,450 --> 00:55:22,700
(Laughter)

810
00:55:22,785 --> 00:55:26,079
Son, son. Six wardens
have been through here in my tenure,

811
00:55:26,163 --> 00:55:29,791
and I've learned one immutable, universal truth.

812
00:55:29,875 --> 00:55:31,584
Not one of them born...

813
00:55:31,585 --> 00:55:36,548
whose asshole wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you asked them for funds.

814
00:55:36,632 --> 00:55:38,925
The budget's stretched thin, as it is.

815
00:55:39,009 --> 00:55:40,260
I see.

816
00:55:40,344 --> 00:55:43,888
Perhaps I could write to the State Senate
and request funds from them.

817
00:55:43,973 --> 00:55:48,351
As far as they're concerned, there's only three
ways to spend money when it comes to prisons:

818
00:55:48,435 --> 00:55:50,520
more walls, more bars and more guards.

819
00:55:50,604 --> 00:55:55,024
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission.
A letter a week. They can't ignore me forever.

820
00:55:55,109 --> 00:55:56,651
Sure can.

821
00:55:56,735 --> 00:55:59,612
But you write your letters, if it makes you happy.

822
00:55:59,697 --> 00:56:01,990
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

823
00:56:03,909 --> 00:56:06,953
RED: So, Andy started writing a letter a week,

824
00:56:07,037 --> 00:56:09,122
just like he said.

825
00:56:13,169 --> 00:56:17,297
And, just like Norton said, Andy got no answers.

826
00:56:25,139 --> 00:56:30,643
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

827
00:56:30,728 --> 00:56:33,813
The year after that, he did them all...

828
00:56:33,898 --> 00:56:35,982
including the Warden's.

829
00:56:37,359 --> 00:56:41,112
The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season

830
00:56:41,197 --> 00:56:43,281
to coincide with tax season.

831
00:56:45,576 --> 00:56:49,787
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

832
00:56:49,872 --> 00:56:54,000
So, Moresby Prison issued you your gun,
but you had to pay for it?

833
00:56:54,084 --> 00:56:55,835
Damn right. The holster, too.

834
00:56:55,920 --> 00:56:57,170
That's tax-deductible.

835
00:56:57,254 --> 00:56:58,421
You can write that off.

836
00:56:58,505 --> 00:57:01,841
RED: Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

837
00:57:01,926 --> 00:57:04,969
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

838
00:57:05,054 --> 00:57:07,096
he was allowed a staff.

839
00:57:07,181 --> 00:57:09,641
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

840
00:57:09,725 --> 00:57:12,393
It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,

841
00:57:12,478 --> 00:57:15,146
and that was fine by me.

842
00:57:15,231 --> 00:57:18,608
And still...he kept sending those letters.

843
00:57:23,906 --> 00:57:25,740
Red, Andy.

844
00:57:25,824 --> 00:57:27,033
It's Brooks.

845
00:57:27,117 --> 00:57:29,577
(Men shouting)
- Watch the door.

846
00:57:29,662 --> 00:57:31,246
Please, Brooks.

847
00:57:31,330 --> 00:57:33,331
- Just calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

848
00:57:33,415 --> 00:57:35,458
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

849
00:57:35,542 --> 00:57:38,628
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

850
00:57:38,712 --> 00:57:41,172
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

851
00:57:41,257 --> 00:57:43,383
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

852
00:57:43,467 --> 00:57:45,176
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

853
00:57:45,261 --> 00:57:47,136
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

854
00:57:47,221 --> 00:57:49,347
It's what they done!

855
00:57:49,431 --> 00:57:50,848
I...I got no choice...

856
00:57:50,933 --> 00:57:53,601
You're not gonna hurt him.
Even Heywood knows that.

857
00:57:53,686 --> 00:57:56,312
- Right, Heywood?
- I...I know that, sure.

858
00:57:56,397 --> 00:57:59,816
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend,
and you're a reasonable man.

859
00:57:59,900 --> 00:58:01,192
That's right. Right, guys?

860
00:58:01,277 --> 00:58:04,654
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

861
00:58:04,738 --> 00:58:06,572
Put the knife down.

862
00:58:07,658 --> 00:58:08,825
Brooks...

863
00:58:08,909 --> 00:58:11,160
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

864
00:58:11,245 --> 00:58:13,579
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

865
00:58:13,664 --> 00:58:14,831
(Heywood gasps)

866
00:58:14,915 --> 00:58:16,499
It's the only...

867
00:58:16,583 --> 00:58:18,876
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

868
00:58:18,961 --> 00:58:21,546
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

869
00:58:21,547 --> 00:58:23,631
Put it down.

870
00:58:24,967 --> 00:58:27,343
(Brooks sobs)

871
00:58:31,015 --> 00:58:35,727
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

872
00:58:35,811 --> 00:58:37,186
HEYWOOD: Him?

873
00:58:37,271 --> 00:58:40,940
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

874
00:58:41,025 --> 00:58:43,651
RED: Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

875
00:58:43,736 --> 00:58:45,987
What the hell did you do to set him off, anyway?

876
00:58:46,071 --> 00:58:48,406
Nothing. I come in here to say fare-thee-well.

877
00:58:48,490 --> 00:58:51,617
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

878
00:58:53,662 --> 00:58:56,789
I just don't understand what happened in there.
That's all.

879
00:58:56,874 --> 00:58:59,459
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

880
00:58:59,543 --> 00:59:01,753
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

881
00:59:01,837 --> 00:59:04,839
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

882
00:59:04,923 --> 00:59:06,299
Would you knock it off?

883
00:59:06,383 --> 00:59:08,718
Brooks ain't no bug.

884
00:59:08,802 --> 00:59:10,678
He's just...

885
00:59:12,556 --> 00:59:14,390
He's just institutionalized.

886
00:59:15,726 --> 00:59:17,393
Institutionalized, my ass.

887
00:59:17,478 --> 00:59:21,773
The man's been in here 50 years, Heywood.
50 years.

888
00:59:21,857 --> 00:59:23,566
This is all he knows.

889
00:59:23,650 --> 00:59:26,069
In here, he's an important man.

890
00:59:26,153 --> 00:59:27,612
He's an educated man.

891
00:59:27,696 --> 00:59:29,781
Outside, he's nothing.

892
00:59:31,950 --> 00:59:34,577
Just a used-up con with arthritis in both hands.

893
00:59:34,661 --> 00:59:37,872
Probably couldn't get a library card if he tried.

894
00:59:37,956 --> 00:59:40,041
You know what I'm trying to say?

895
00:59:40,125 --> 00:59:42,877
Red, I do believe you're talking out of your ass.

896
00:59:44,129 --> 00:59:47,048
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

897
00:59:47,049 --> 00:59:49,592
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

898
00:59:51,011 --> 00:59:53,096
First you hate 'em...

899
00:59:54,640 --> 00:59:56,724
..then you get used to 'em.

900
00:59:58,352 --> 01:00:00,978
Enough time passes...

901
01:00:01,063 --> 01:00:04,023
you get so you depend on 'em.

902
01:00:04,108 --> 01:00:06,442
That's institutionalized.

903
01:00:06,527 --> 01:00:07,902
JIGGER: Shit.

904
01:00:07,903 --> 01:00:09,529
You can never get like that.

905
01:00:09,613 --> 01:00:11,531
Oh, yeah?

906
01:00:11,615 --> 01:00:14,200
Say that when you've been here
as long as Brooks has.

907
01:00:14,284 --> 01:00:16,160
Goddamn right.

908
01:00:18,497 --> 01:00:21,040
They send you here for life.

909
01:00:21,125 --> 01:00:23,209
That's exactly what they take.

910
01:00:25,129 --> 01:00:27,213
The part that counts, anyway.

911
01:00:30,259 --> 01:00:33,594
(Jake screeches)

912
01:00:34,721 --> 01:00:36,889
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

913
01:00:38,809 --> 01:00:40,643
You go on, now.

914
01:00:41,728 --> 01:00:46,399
You're free.

915
01:01:02,291 --> 01:01:04,167
Bye.

916
01:01:05,252 --> 01:01:07,170
Good luck, Brooks.

917
01:01:43,749 --> 01:01:46,459
BROOKS: Dear fellas...

918
01:01:46,543 --> 01:01:50,755
I can't believe
how fast things move on the outside.

919
01:01:50,839 --> 01:01:52,089
(Horn blares)

920
01:01:52,174 --> 01:01:55,218
Watch it, old-timer! Are you trying to get killed?

921
01:01:55,302 --> 01:01:58,638
I saw an automobile once, when I was a kid,

922
01:01:58,722 --> 01:02:01,641
but now...they're everywhere.

923
01:02:05,854 --> 01:02:09,440
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

924
01:02:25,791 --> 01:02:32,088
The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,

925
01:02:32,172 --> 01:02:35,967
and a job bagging groceries at the Foodway.

926
01:02:38,011 --> 01:02:43,349
It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.

927
01:02:43,433 --> 01:02:45,434
WOMAN: Make sure your man double-bags.

928
01:02:45,519 --> 01:02:47,770
Last time, the bottom near came out.

929
01:02:47,854 --> 01:02:51,148
Make sure you double-bag, like the lady says.
Understand?

930
01:02:51,233 --> 01:02:52,692
Yes, sir. I surely will.

931
01:02:52,776 --> 01:02:56,571
BROOKS: I don't think
the store manager likes me very much.

932
01:02:56,655 --> 01:02:58,447
(Pigeons cooing)

933
01:02:59,533 --> 01:03:04,328
Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

934
01:03:04,413 --> 01:03:09,750
I keep thinking Jake might just show up
and say hello.

935
01:03:09,835 --> 01:03:11,627
But he never does.

936
01:03:12,713 --> 01:03:18,092
And I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.

937
01:03:21,597 --> 01:03:24,515
I have trouble sleeping at night.

938
01:03:24,600 --> 01:03:27,393
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

939
01:03:28,478 --> 01:03:30,396
I wake up, scared.

940
01:03:30,480 --> 01:03:34,483
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

941
01:03:36,111 --> 01:03:37,570
Maybe I should get me a gun

942
01:03:37,654 --> 01:03:41,532
and rob the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

943
01:03:41,617 --> 01:03:43,951
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

944
01:03:44,036 --> 01:03:45,995
Sort of like a bonus.

945
01:03:47,497 --> 01:03:51,751
I guess I'm too old for that sort of nonsense
any more.

946
01:03:51,835 --> 01:03:53,878
I don't like it here.

947
01:03:53,962 --> 01:03:56,631
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

948
01:03:56,715 --> 01:03:57,798
I've decided...

949
01:03:57,883 --> 01:03:59,759
not to stay.

950
01:04:11,104 --> 01:04:14,607
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.

951
01:04:14,691 --> 01:04:16,776
Not for an old crook like me.

952
01:04:31,625 --> 01:04:33,542
(Scraping)

953
01:05:19,798 --> 01:05:23,843
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

954
01:05:25,011 --> 01:05:29,056
PS. Tell Heywood
I'm sorry I put a knife to his throat.

955
01:05:29,057 --> 01:05:31,142
No hard feelings. Brooks."

956
01:05:41,862 --> 01:05:43,946
He should have died in here.

957
01:05:49,369 --> 01:05:53,831
HADLEY: What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

958
01:05:58,545 --> 01:05:59,962
What's all this?

959
01:06:00,046 --> 01:06:03,924
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

960
01:06:04,009 --> 01:06:05,301
Take it.

961
01:06:14,269 --> 01:06:15,853
"Dear Mr. Dufresne...

962
01:06:16,938 --> 01:06:18,939
In response to your repeated enquiries,

963
01:06:19,024 --> 01:06:23,736
the State has allocated the enclosed funds
for your library project."

964
01:06:23,820 --> 01:06:25,196
This is 200 dollars.

965
01:06:26,239 --> 01:06:30,159
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

966
01:06:30,243 --> 01:06:32,953
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

967
01:06:33,038 --> 01:06:35,122
We trust this will fill your needs.

968
01:06:35,207 --> 01:06:39,335
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

969
01:06:39,419 --> 01:06:42,254
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

970
01:06:42,339 --> 01:06:44,006
Yes, sir.

971
01:06:47,761 --> 01:06:49,136
Good for you, Andy.

972
01:06:51,765 --> 01:06:53,224
Wow!

973
01:06:54,309 --> 01:06:56,393
It only took six years.

974
01:06:57,687 --> 01:07:00,564
From now on,
I'll write two letters a week, instead of one.

975
01:07:00,649 --> 01:07:04,193
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out,

976
01:07:04,277 --> 01:07:05,444
like the Captain said.

977
01:07:05,529 --> 01:07:09,406
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

978
01:07:15,580 --> 01:07:17,581
Wow.

