It's got to land on somebody.

1511
01:42:32,862 --> 01:42:35,113
It was my turn, that's all.

1512
01:42:36,199 --> 01:42:38,659
I was in the path of the tornado.

1513
01:42:45,249 --> 01:42:49,002
I just didn't expect
the storm would last as long as it has.

1514
01:42:53,091 --> 01:42:55,008
Do you think you'll ever get out of here?

1515
01:42:56,260 --> 01:42:57,928
Me?

1516
01:43:00,223 --> 01:43:01,682
Yeah.

1517
01:43:02,725 --> 01:43:04,685
One day, when I've got a long, white beard

1518
01:43:04,769 --> 01:43:08,271
and two or three marbles rolling around upstairs,
they'll let me out.

1519
01:43:10,191 --> 01:43:12,275
I tell you where I'd go.

1520
01:43:13,486 --> 01:43:15,112
Zihuatanejo.

1521
01:43:15,196 --> 01:43:17,114
Zi...what?

1522
01:43:17,198 --> 01:43:19,241
Zihuatanejo.

1523
01:43:19,325 --> 01:43:21,410
It's in Mexico.

1524
01:43:23,204 --> 01:43:25,414
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1525
01:43:26,666 --> 01:43:29,042
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1526
01:43:29,127 --> 01:43:30,585
No.

1527
01:43:30,670 --> 01:43:32,754
They say it has no memory.

1528
01:43:35,216 --> 01:43:37,759
That's where I want to live the rest of my life.

1529
01:43:39,345 --> 01:43:41,430
A warm place with no memory.

1530
01:43:44,726 --> 01:43:47,019
Open up a little hotel,

1531
01:43:48,855 --> 01:43:50,731
right on the beach.

1532
01:43:50,815 --> 01:43:52,858
Buy some worthless old boat,

1533
01:43:52,942 --> 01:43:55,027
fix it up new.

1534
01:43:57,989 --> 01:43:59,197
Take my guests out.

1535
01:43:59,282 --> 01:44:01,366
Charter fishing.

1536
01:44:05,288 --> 01:44:07,914
Zihuatanejo, huh?

1537
01:44:10,543 --> 01:44:14,421
In a place like that, I could use a man
who knows how to get things.

1538
01:44:20,845 --> 01:44:23,555
I don't think I could make it on the outside, Andy.

1539
01:44:30,313 --> 01:44:32,397
I've been in here most of my life.

1540
01:44:33,900 --> 01:44:35,692
I'm an institutional man now.

1541
01:44:35,777 --> 01:44:37,861
Just like Brooks was.

1542
01:44:39,280 --> 01:44:41,531
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1543
01:44:41,616 --> 01:44:43,700
I don't think so.

1544
01:44:46,329 --> 01:44:50,540
I mean...in here, I'm the guy
who can get things for you, sure.

1545
01:44:50,625 --> 01:44:54,544
But outside, all you need is the Yellow Pages.

1546
01:44:54,629 --> 01:44:57,047
Hell, I wouldn't even know where to begin.

1547
01:44:59,133 --> 01:45:01,468
The Pacific Ocean?

1548
01:45:01,552 --> 01:45:03,595
Shit.

1549
01:45:03,679 --> 01:45:06,848
- About scare me to death, something that big.
- Not me.

1550
01:45:06,933 --> 01:45:10,393
I didn't shoot my wife and I didn't shoot her lover.

1551
01:45:12,313 --> 01:45:15,941
Whatever mistakes I've made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1552
01:45:16,025 --> 01:45:18,193
That hotel, that boat.

1553
01:45:19,779 --> 01:45:21,947
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1554
01:45:26,577 --> 01:45:29,454
I don't think you ought to be
doing this to yourself, Andy.

1555
01:45:29,539 --> 01:45:31,581
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1556
01:45:31,666 --> 01:45:34,626
I mean, Mexico is way the hell down there
and you're in here.

1557
01:45:34,710 --> 01:45:36,753
And that's the way it is.

1558
01:45:36,838 --> 01:45:39,464
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1559
01:45:41,217 --> 01:45:43,301
It's down there and I'm in here.

1560
01:45:46,013 --> 01:45:48,807
I guess it comes down to a simple choice, really.

1561
01:45:51,644 --> 01:45:53,687
Get busy living

1562
01:45:53,771 --> 01:45:56,690
or get busy dying.

1563
01:46:00,486 --> 01:46:02,571
Andy.

1564
01:46:05,032 --> 01:46:07,117
Red.

1565
01:46:08,161 --> 01:46:10,579
If you ever get out of here, do me a favor.

1566
01:46:10,663 --> 01:46:12,497
Sure, Andy.

1567
01:46:12,582 --> 01:46:13,915
Anything.

1568
01:46:15,001 --> 01:46:18,461
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1569
01:46:20,464 --> 01:46:24,259
- Well, just... There's a lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1570
01:46:24,343 --> 01:46:26,386
It's got a long rock wall

1571
01:46:26,470 --> 01:46:28,388
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1572
01:46:28,472 --> 01:46:31,183
It's like something out of a Robert Frost poem.

1573
01:46:32,560 --> 01:46:35,270
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1574
01:46:36,480 --> 01:46:40,275
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1575
01:46:41,777 --> 01:46:43,862
I asked and she said yes.

1576
01:46:47,992 --> 01:46:50,035
Promise me, Red,

1577
01:46:50,119 --> 01:46:52,120
if you ever get out,

1578
01:46:52,205 --> 01:46:54,247
find that spot.

1579
01:46:55,291 --> 01:47:00,754
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that has
no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1580
01:47:00,838 --> 01:47:03,340
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1581
01:47:06,510 --> 01:47:09,304
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1582
01:47:09,388 --> 01:47:11,389
What, Andy?

1583
01:47:11,474 --> 01:47:13,558
What's buried under there?

1584
01:47:15,353 --> 01:47:18,730
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1585
01:47:24,070 --> 01:47:26,154
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1586
01:47:27,198 --> 01:47:29,282
He's talking funnier.

1587
01:47:29,367 --> 01:47:32,744
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1588
01:47:32,828 --> 01:47:36,873
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1589
01:47:37,959 --> 01:47:39,417
Oh, Lord.

1590
01:47:39,502 --> 01:47:41,544
What?

1591
01:47:43,214 --> 01:47:45,548
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1592
01:47:45,633 --> 01:47:49,135
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1593
01:47:49,220 --> 01:47:51,054
Six feet long.

1594
01:47:51,138 --> 01:47:52,597
And you gave it to him?

1595
01:47:52,682 --> 01:47:55,350
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1596
01:47:55,351 --> 01:47:57,060
Jesus, Heywood.

1597
01:47:57,144 --> 01:47:59,396
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1598
01:47:59,480 --> 01:48:01,398
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1599
01:48:01,482 --> 01:48:02,524
No.

1600
01:48:03,567 --> 01:48:05,777
Andy would never do that.

1601
01:48:05,778 --> 01:48:07,862
Never.

1602
01:48:08,906 --> 01:48:10,991
I don't know.

1603
01:48:13,035 --> 01:48:15,120
Every man has his breaking point.

1604
01:48:17,748 --> 01:48:18,999
Lickety-split.

1605
01:48:19,083 --> 01:48:21,960
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1606
01:48:38,060 --> 01:48:40,145
Three deposits tonight.

1607
01:48:48,529 --> 01:48:50,613
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1608
01:48:50,614 --> 01:48:54,075
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1609
01:48:54,160 --> 01:48:55,535
Yes, sir.

1610
01:49:00,833 --> 01:49:02,500
It's good having you back, Andy.

1611
01:49:02,585 --> 01:49:05,337
The place wasn't the same without you.

1612
01:49:07,465 --> 01:49:09,549
(Whistles)

1613
01:49:52,385 --> 01:49:55,136
GUARD: Lights out!
(Click of light switches)

1614
01:49:59,433 --> 01:50:01,518
(Footsteps)

1615
01:50:07,400 --> 01:50:09,484
(Outer door closes)

1616
01:50:25,876 --> 01:50:28,169
RED: I've had some long nights in stir.

1617
01:50:29,213 --> 01:50:31,923
Alone in the dark with nothing but your thoughts,

1618
01:50:32,007 --> 01:50:33,842
time can draw out like a blade.

1619
01:50:33,843 --> 01:50:35,927
(Thunder rumbles)

1620
01:50:40,224 --> 01:50:42,559
That was the longest night of my life.

1621
01:50:52,778 --> 01:50:55,113
(Gate buzzer)

1622
01:50:58,701 --> 01:51:00,326
GUARD: Give me a count.

1623
01:51:04,665 --> 01:51:06,708
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1624
01:51:06,792 --> 01:51:08,126
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1625
01:51:08,210 --> 01:51:11,796
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1626
01:51:11,881 --> 01:51:14,966
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1627
01:51:15,050 --> 01:51:17,969
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1628
01:51:20,473 --> 01:51:24,517
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1629
01:51:32,109 --> 01:51:35,487
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1630
01:51:35,571 --> 01:51:38,656
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1631
01:51:38,741 --> 01:51:40,575
You hear me?

1632
01:51:47,082 --> 01:51:49,167
Oh, my holy God.

1633
01:52:01,263 --> 01:52:03,348
(Siren wails)

1634
01:52:06,018 --> 01:52:08,728
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1635
01:52:08,729 --> 01:52:10,939
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1636
01:52:11,023 --> 01:52:12,232
Him!

1637
01:52:14,151 --> 01:52:16,236
Open 237.

1638
01:52:19,240 --> 01:52:21,366
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1639
01:52:21,450 --> 01:52:22,992
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1640
01:52:23,077 --> 01:52:25,328
Don't say that to me again.

1641
01:52:25,412 --> 01:52:26,496
But, sir, he wasn't.

1642
01:52:26,580 --> 01:52:28,748
I can see that, Haig!

1643
01:52:28,832 --> 01:52:30,625
You think I'm blind?

1644
01:52:30,626 --> 01:52:33,753
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1645
01:52:33,837 --> 01:52:34,837
No, sir.

1646
01:52:34,922 --> 01:52:36,965
What about you?

1647
01:52:37,049 --> 01:52:38,883
Are you blind?

1648
01:52:38,968 --> 01:52:41,511
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1649
01:52:41,595 --> 01:52:44,889
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1650
01:52:44,974 --> 01:52:46,849
Dufresne.

1651
01:52:48,102 --> 01:52:49,769
He was in his cell at lights out.

1652
01:52:49,853 --> 01:52:53,064
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1653
01:52:54,149 --> 01:52:56,025
I want him found.

1654
01:52:56,110 --> 01:52:58,695
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1655
01:52:58,779 --> 01:52:59,821
Now!

1656
01:52:59,822 --> 01:53:01,322
Yes, sir!

1657
01:53:02,449 --> 01:53:05,034
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1658
01:53:07,871 --> 01:53:08,913
Stand.

1659
01:53:10,040 --> 01:53:11,291
Well?

1660
01:53:14,670 --> 01:53:15,795
Well, what?

1661
01:53:15,879 --> 01:53:19,340
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1662
01:53:20,384 --> 01:53:22,010
He must have said something.

1663
01:53:22,094 --> 01:53:24,137
No, sir, Warden.

1664
01:53:24,221 --> 01:53:25,680
Not a word.

1665
01:53:27,683 --> 01:53:29,684
Lord, it's a miracle!

1666
01:53:30,728 --> 01:53:33,187
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1667
01:53:33,272 --> 01:53:35,023
Nothing left but...

1668
01:53:35,107 --> 01:53:38,026
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1669
01:53:38,110 --> 01:53:39,861
And that cupcake on the wall.

1670
01:53:39,945 --> 01:53:41,571
Let's ask her.

1671
01:53:41,655 --> 01:53:45,617
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1672
01:53:46,702 --> 01:53:47,785
Ah...

1673
01:53:47,786 --> 01:53:49,245
I guess not.

1674
01:53:49,330 --> 01:53:52,206
Why should she be any different?

1675
01:53:52,291 --> 01:53:54,751
This is a conspiracy.

1676
01:53:54,835 --> 01:53:57,045
That's what this is.

1677
01:53:57,129 --> 01:53:58,671
One big...

1678
01:53:58,756 --> 01:54:01,507
damn conspiracy!

1679
01:54:01,592 --> 01:54:04,260
And everyone's in on it!

1680
01:54:04,345 --> 01:54:05,637
Including her!

1681
01:54:06,972 --> 01:54:08,640
(Clattering)

1682
01:54:32,414 --> 01:54:34,123
(Sirens blare)

1683
01:54:40,297 --> 01:54:42,173
RED: In 1966,

1684
01:54:42,257 --> 01:54:44,926
Andy Dufresne escaped

1685
01:54:45,010 --> 01:54:47,095
from Shawshank Prison.

1686
01:54:48,764 --> 01:54:51,516
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1687
01:54:51,600 --> 01:54:53,643
a bar of soap

1688
01:54:53,727 --> 01:54:58,106
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1689
01:55:02,486 --> 01:55:07,323
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1690
01:55:07,408 --> 01:55:10,118
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1691
01:55:28,679 --> 01:55:30,763
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1692
01:55:31,807 --> 01:55:35,309
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1693
01:55:35,394 --> 01:55:37,687
An Ice Age here,

1694
01:55:37,771 --> 01:55:40,356
a million years of mountain-building there.

1695
01:55:41,400 --> 01:55:43,818
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1696
01:55:45,028 --> 01:55:47,071
That's all it takes, really.

1697
01:55:47,156 --> 01:55:49,198
Pressure...

1698
01:55:49,283 --> 01:55:51,159
and time.

1699
01:55:51,243 --> 01:55:54,579
That and a big goddamn poster.

1700
01:55:55,664 --> 01:55:57,707
(Coughing)

1701
01:55:57,791 --> 01:55:59,167
Like I said,

1702
01:55:59,168 --> 01:56:02,962
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1703
01:56:05,758 --> 01:56:10,928
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1704
01:56:11,013 --> 01:56:13,097
A handful at a time.

1705
01:56:14,933 --> 01:56:17,101
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1706
01:56:17,186 --> 01:56:20,021
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1707
01:56:20,105 --> 01:56:22,315
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1708
01:56:23,609 --> 01:56:25,693
I'm just about finished, sir.

1709
01:56:47,090 --> 01:56:49,175
Three deposits tonight.

1710
01:56:56,350 --> 01:56:58,392
Andy did like he was told.

1711
01:56:59,436 --> 01:57:02,939
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1712
01:57:06,527 --> 01:57:08,569
The guard simply didn't notice.

1713
01:57:08,654 --> 01:57:10,696
Neither did I.

1714
01:57:10,781 --> 01:57:15,117
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1715
01:57:49,820 --> 01:57:51,904
(Thunderclap)

1716
01:59:19,159 --> 01:59:25,331
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1717
01:59:25,415 --> 01:59:26,582
(Gags)

1718
01:59:26,667 --> 01:59:28,668
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1719
01:59:28,752 --> 01:59:30,836
(Coughs and spits)

1720
01:59:33,382 --> 01:59:35,591
500 yards.

1721
01:59:36,635 --> 01:59:39,136
That's the length of five football fields.

1722
01:59:40,180 --> 01:59:42,431
Just shy of half a mile.

1723
02:00:23,974 --> 02:00:25,683
(Laughs)

1724
02:00:37,654 --> 02:00:42,199
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1725
02:00:42,284 --> 02:00:45,703
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1726
02:00:45,787 --> 02:00:48,205
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1727
02:00:48,290 --> 02:00:50,332
Until that moment,

1728
02:00:50,417 --> 02:00:52,293
he didn't exist,

1729
02:00:52,377 --> 02:00:53,711
except on paper.

1730
02:00:53,795 --> 02:00:54,837
May I help you?

1731
02:00:54,921 --> 02:00:56,964
RED: He had all the proper ID,

1732
02:00:57,049 --> 02:01:00,676
driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.

1733
02:01:00,761 --> 02:01:04,055
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1734
02:01:04,139 --> 02:01:07,183
I must say, I'm sorry to be losing your business.

1735
02:01:07,267 --> 02:01:09,268
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1736
02:01:09,352 --> 02:01:11,145
Thank you.

1737
02:01:11,229 --> 02:01:13,022
I'm sure I will.

1738
02:01:13,106 --> 02:01:15,232
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1739
02:01:15,317 --> 02:01:17,359
Will there be anything else?

1740
02:01:17,444 --> 02:01:18,444
Please...

1741
02:01:18,528 --> 02:01:21,614
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1742
02:01:21,698 --> 02:01:23,908
I'd be happy to.

1743
02:01:23,992 --> 02:01:26,327
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1744
02:01:26,411 --> 02:01:31,207
RED: Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1745
02:01:32,375 --> 02:01:38,839
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1746
02:01:38,924 --> 02:01:41,383
Severance pay for 19 years.

1747
02:01:41,468 --> 02:01:43,552
(Phone rings)

1748
02:01:49,518 --> 02:01:51,811
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1749
02:01:59,486 --> 02:02:01,570
(Sirens wail)

1750
02:02:30,767 --> 02:02:32,810
(Sirens approaching)

1751
02:02:44,531 --> 02:02:47,533
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1752
02:02:47,617 --> 02:02:52,246
If you give up the right to remain silent, anything
you say will be held against you in court.

1753
02:02:52,330 --> 02:02:54,206
RED: I wasn't there to see it.

1754
02:02:54,291 --> 02:02:59,170
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1755
02:03:04,593 --> 02:03:07,386
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1756
02:03:23,361 --> 02:03:24,820
Samuel Norton?

1757
02:03:24,905 --> 02:03:28,157
- We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.
(Banging on door)

1758
02:03:31,036 --> 02:03:32,161
Norton!

1759
02:03:32,245 --> 02:03:33,913
Open the door.

1760
02:03:33,997 --> 02:03:35,748
I'm not sure which key it is.

1761
02:03:38,627 --> 02:03:40,294
Norton!

1762
02:03:45,759 --> 02:03:47,843
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1763
02:03:59,147 --> 02:04:02,733
RED: I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,

1764
02:04:02,817 --> 02:04:04,526
other than that bullet,

1765
02:04:04,611 --> 02:04:08,614
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1766
02:04:10,283 --> 02:04:11,367
Carter, James...

1767
02:04:11,451 --> 02:04:14,828
RED: Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1768
02:04:14,913 --> 02:04:17,164
I got a postcard in the mail.

1769
02:04:18,875 --> 02:04:21,293
It was blank but the postmark said...

1770
02:04:21,378 --> 02:04:24,129
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1771
02:04:24,214 --> 02:04:26,257
Fort Hancock.

1772
02:04:26,341 --> 02:04:28,384
Right on the border.

1773
02:04:28,468 --> 02:04:30,511
That's where Andy crossed.

1774
02:04:30,595 --> 02:04:34,473
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1775
02:04:35,517 --> 02:04:37,601
it always makes me laugh.

1776
02:04:39,020 --> 02:04:41,063
Andy Dufresne,

1777
02:04:41,147 --> 02:04:43,524
who crawled through a river of shit

1778
02:04:43,608 --> 02:04:45,693
and came out clean on the other side.

1779
02:04:46,903 --> 02:04:48,946
Andy Dufresne,

1780
02:04:49,030 --> 02:04:50,948
headed for the Pacific.

1781
02:04:53,535 --> 02:04:55,577
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1782
02:04:55,662 --> 02:04:59,873
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1783
02:04:59,958 --> 02:05:03,127
RED: Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1784
02:05:03,211 --> 02:05:05,462
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1785
02:05:05,547 --> 02:05:08,048
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1786
02:05:08,133 --> 02:05:10,217
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1787
02:05:11,386 --> 02:05:13,762
RED: Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1788
02:05:13,847 --> 02:05:15,889
Andy being gone.

1789
02:05:15,974 --> 02:05:19,977
I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1790
02:05:21,062 --> 02:05:23,147
Their feathers are just too bright.

1791
02:05:24,691 --> 02:05:26,734
And when they fly away,

1792
02:05:26,818 --> 02:05:30,738
the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1793
02:05:32,490 --> 02:05:33,949
But still...

1794
02:05:34,034 --> 02:05:38,203
the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.

1795
02:05:42,751 --> 02:05:45,002
I guess I just miss my friend.

1796
02:06:08,985 --> 02:06:10,861
Please sit down.

1797
02:06:16,451 --> 02:06:18,577
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1798
02:06:18,661 --> 02:06:22,039
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1799
02:06:22,123 --> 02:06:24,500
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1800
02:06:26,628 --> 02:06:28,712
Rehabilitated?

1801
02:06:30,256 --> 02:06:32,341
Well, now, let me see.

1802
02:06:33,385 --> 02:06:35,719
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1803
02:06:37,514 --> 02:06:40,057
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1804
02:06:40,141 --> 02:06:42,684
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1805
02:06:45,063 --> 02:06:47,147
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1806
02:06:48,191 --> 02:06:50,442
A politician's word so that...

1807
02:06:50,527 --> 02:06:56,031
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1808
02:06:58,451 --> 02:07:00,536
What do you really want to know?

1809
02:07:01,704 --> 02:07:03,622
Am I sorry for what I did?

1810
02:07:03,706 --> 02:07:05,416
Well, are you?

1811
02:07:07,043 --> 02:07:09,628
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1812
02:07:11,214 --> 02:07:14,341
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1813
02:07:18,138 --> 02:07:20,222
I look back on the way I was then.

1814
02:07:22,809 --> 02:07:24,852
A young...

1815
02:07:24,936 --> 02:07:28,021
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1816
02:07:31,860 --> 02:07:33,944
I wanna talk to him.

1817
02:07:35,321 --> 02:07:37,489
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1818
02:07:38,533 --> 02:07:40,617
tell him the way things are.

1819
02:07:42,787 --> 02:07:44,872
But I can't.

1820
02:07:46,082 --> 02:07:48,167
That kid's long gone.

1821
02:07:49,461 --> 02:07:51,545
This old man is all that's left.

1822
02:07:53,673 --> 02:07:55,174
I gotta live with that.

1823
02:07:56,509 --> 02:07:58,302
Rehabilitated?

1824
02:07:58,386 --> 02:08:00,387
It's just a bullshit word.

1825
02:08:00,472 --> 02:08:06,393
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1826
02:08:07,479 --> 02:08:09,521
Because to tell you the truth,

1827
02:08:09,606 --> 02:08:12,107
I don't give a shit.

1828
02:08:50,230 --> 02:08:52,314
(Gate closes)

1829
02:09:11,709 --> 02:09:13,794
(Siren passes outside)

1830
02:09:38,319 --> 02:09:40,404
Here you go, miss.

1831
02:09:42,407 --> 02:09:43,865
Rest room break, boss?

1832
02:09:49,914 --> 02:09:54,209
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1833
02:09:55,420 --> 02:09:57,087
Yes, sir.

1834
02:10:07,140 --> 02:10:10,183
RED: 40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.

1835
02:10:11,185 --> 02:10:13,395
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1836
02:10:17,525 --> 02:10:19,610
There's a harsh truth to face.

1837
02:10:21,571 --> 02:10:23,905
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1838
02:10:32,123 --> 02:10:35,584
All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...

1839
02:10:36,628 --> 02:10:38,712
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1840
02:10:44,218 --> 02:10:46,303
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1841
02:10:47,680 --> 02:10:51,058
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1842
02:10:53,227 --> 02:10:56,021
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1843
02:10:57,065 --> 02:10:59,566
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1844
02:11:02,445 --> 02:11:04,529
Only one thing stops me.

1845
02:11:05,573 --> 02:11:07,658
A promise I made to Andy.

1846
02:11:28,388 --> 02:11:30,472
Here it is.

1847
02:11:40,274 --> 02:11:42,359
Much obliged, sir.

1848
02:15:05,605 --> 02:15:07,689
(Bird calls)

1849
02:15:21,162 --> 02:15:22,454
ANDY: Dear Red,

1850
02:15:22,538 --> 02:15:24,998
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1851
02:15:25,082 --> 02:15:29,336
And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1852
02:15:29,420 --> 02:15:32,005
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1853
02:15:34,300 --> 02:15:36,384
Zihuatanejo.

1854
02:15:37,428 --> 02:15:38,637
I could use a good man

1855
02:15:38,721 --> 02:15:40,764
to help me get my project on wheels.

1856
02:15:40,848 --> 02:15:42,974
I'll keep an eye out for you

1857
02:15:43,059 --> 02:15:45,101
and the chessboard ready.

1858
02:15:46,145 --> 02:15:47,520
Remember, Red,

1859
02:15:47,605 --> 02:15:49,648
hope is a good thing.

1860
02:15:49,732 --> 02:15:51,775
Maybe the best of things.

1861
02:15:51,859 --> 02:15:53,944
And no good thing ever dies.

1862
02:15:54,987 --> 02:15:57,447
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1863
02:15:57,531 --> 02:15:59,574
and finds you well.

1864
02:15:59,659 --> 02:16:02,160
Your friend, Andy.

1865
02:16:36,737 --> 02:16:40,615
RED: Get busy living or get busy dying.

1866
02:16:43,119 --> 02:16:45,203
That's goddamn right.

1867
02:16:50,710 --> 02:16:52,836
For the second time in my life,

1868
02:16:52,920 --> 02:16:55,005
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1869
02:16:56,674 --> 02:16:58,758
Parole violation.

1870
02:16:58,759 --> 02:17:02,470
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1871
02:17:03,723 --> 02:17:05,765
Not for an old crook like me.

1872
02:17:05,850 --> 02:17:07,934
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1873
02:17:11,647 --> 02:17:15,775
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.

1874
02:17:16,819 --> 02:17:19,821
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1875
02:17:19,905 --> 02:17:22,615
A free man at the start of a long journey

1876
02:17:22,700 --> 02:17:25,618
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1877
02:17:28,497 --> 02:17:30,665
I hope I can make it across the border.

1878
02:17:32,543 --> 02:17:35,336
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1879
02:17:37,715 --> 02:17:40,925
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1880
02:17:43,679 --> 02:17:45,555
I hope.

